Major refrigeration process equipment includes the following:
a) compressors;
b) condensers;
c) high pressure receiver;
d) pumping units;
e) evaporators, air handling units, and water chillers
f) diffuser (emergency only).

The entire refrigeration system has the capacity to hold 20,000 pounds of anhydrous ammonia in a closed loop system.

Under a separate process, anhydrous ammonia 1,200 pounds maximum inventory is used in a Selective Catalytic Reduction (SCR) system to control nitrogen oxides (NOX) emissions from a one Mega Watt natural gas fired turbine. The ammonia is stored in an ASME-rated Pressure Vessel.  This process utilizes anhydrous ammonia in the capacity of a SCR for the Best Available Control Technology (BACT). The SCR system reduces NOX emissions by injecting ammonia into the exhaust gas stream upstream of a catalyst matrix. Nitrogen oxides, ammonia, and oxygen react on the surface of the catalyst to form nitrogen and water. The catalyst is comprised of a noble metal and works within a high temperature range for proper operations (800A? F to 1100A?F). As such, the control efficiency of the SCR system is reducing NOX emissions to about 90 percent.  As described above, this system is offline unless needed under imminent or power failure conditions.

1.3 Summary of the General Accidental Release Prevention Program and Chemical Specific Prevention Steps

Accidental Release Prevention Program
The design of the Refrigeration & SCR systems along with the implementation of the Cal/ARP Level III Prevention Program (Process Safety Management or PSM) is specifically intended to provide assurance that the risks associated with ammonia are effectively managed.  Gill's Onions developed the facility

Process Safety Management (PSM) Program pursuant to Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) guidelines (i.e., 8 CCR A?5189).  Gill's Onions first implemented the PSM program on June 18, 1999.  Improvements have been made over time including revisions resulting from a targeted Cal/OSHA PSM Inspection in 2002.  The elements of the Prevention Program are intended to be integrated with the daily and ongoing functions of the facility, and to integrate with other safety programs to the extent possible. The programs implemented by GillA?s Onions should enable the facility to prevent an occurrence and minimize the consequences of a release of Anhydrous Ammonia.  Compliance with RMP, PSM and Cal/ARPA?s comprehensive program ensures the integrity of the Processes that handle flammable or toxic materials. The objectives of the regulation(s) are specifically to prevent unwanted releases of hazardous chemicals. To control these types of hazards, Gills Onions has developed the necessary expertise, experiences, judgment and proactive initiative within their workforce to properly implement and maintain an effective Prevention Program. 

The twelve elements that make up the Prevention Program 3 (PSM) are:
1.   Process Safety Information;
2.   Process Hazard Analysis (PHA);
3.   Operating Procedures;
4.   Training;
5.   Mechanical Integrity;
6.   Management of Change;
7.   Pre-Startup Review;
8.   Compliance Audits;
9.   Incident Investigation;
10. Employee Participation;
11. Hot Work Permit; and,
12. Contractors

