1.5  Emergency Response Program (ERP)

Gill's Onions has developed written emergency procedures to address elements that may be encountered during planning, responding or follow-up to an emergency at the facility. Application of the emergency procedures ensures compliance with OSHA Standard 29 CFR 1910.38 (Emergency Action Plans) within the emergency response element of the Risk Management Plan. The basic concept of Gill's Onions emergency procedures are to provide a comprehensive approach for managing emergencies. The four elements of this approach are prevention, preparedness, response, and recovery.

The Plant does not require its employees to participate in conducting emergency response activities under the HAZWOPER standard; a A?Non-responding Facility PolicyA? has been adopted.  Plant employees are to implement hazard communications, provide for the safety of visitors and report to the established Evacuation Staging Area(s) for a head count.  Emergency response is coordinated with the City of Oxnard Fire/CUPA.  The Refrigeration Plant Operator and/or other Management would be available to support the Fire Department as technical resources.  The facility has communicated with Oxnard Fire/CUPA to be included in the Oxnard Community Emergency Plan.     

The ERP is designed to be applicable to any type of emergency that may affect Gill's Onions and based on the concept that the elements of emergency response are similar, regardless of the hazard. The ERP comprises the following sections:

1. Agency Interface and Response Planning;
2. Public and Agency Notification;
3. Emergency Medical Care;
4. Emergency Response Actions;
5. Emergency Equipment;
6. Emergency Response Training;
7. Incident Command System; and
8. Plan Review and Update.

Gill's Onions emergency response procedures serve as a guide for emergency control staff, company personnel, emergency assistance groups and law enforcement age

ncies that may be called upon to participate in controlling an emergency within the facility and surrounding areas. These procedures include employee notification of emergencies and evacuation procedures for emergency situations.  The facility is equipped with windsocks to help determine safe evacuation routes and staging areas.

1.6 Planned Changes to Improve Safety

The primary mechanisms to identify and plan safety improvements include (but are not limited to):
A?    Process Hazard Analysis revalidation/update;
A?    Compliance Audits;
A?    Routine inspections, tests & maintenance (Mechanical Integrity Program);
A?    IIAR Bulletin 109 Inspections (IIAR minimum safety criteria for the safe operation of ammonia refrigeration process);
A?    GillA?s Onions Internal Inspection Protocols

The programs above may result in recommendations ranging from capital improvements to routine maintenance of the plant.  Where appropriate Work Orders are established in parallel to identified needs.  Current planned changes to improve safety include recommendations as a result of the Process Hazard Analysis Revalidation/Update performed May 26, 2009.  A written implementation schedule has been prepared.  Recommendations are scheduled for completion by August 01, 2009.  A summary includes:  Ensure review of signage (fading) and vegetation growth (buildup) is on the walk-through checklist; Review Fire Prevention Plan; Install new signage for restricted areas, Review policy regarding restricted areas - add or revise employee training program if needed; review written PSM Program for QC of replacement parts; Check that Compressor manufacturer procedures include checking motor rotation on repairA?amend if needed; Validate SOPA?s and PIDA?s for Valve Tags; Review SOPA?s to ensure specific PPE requirements for specific tasks are appropriately addressed.
